Species Comments: Found a chick, alone, on the side of the road. We left it where it was, but later found out that a trucker had picked it up and taken it as a pet.

Species Comments: Edit after the fact (2/14/2018): this observation on 2/2/2018 was the first time I saw Kites in this tree. I have seen them several times since - they always seem to arrive just before sunset. So far, six is still the high count, but they have been there every day I have looked for them at sunset (which is now several times). They are near the top of a tall deciduous tree behind the backyards on the west side of Acton (around this 2128 address).

As with many other days, when I looked for them (from Charlie Dorr park) at about 30 minutes before sunset, they weren't there. But when I walked past right at sunset (~5:50), there were three. Most I have seen in this tree is six at a time (that was slightly later - maybe more would have come this time had I waited).

Three seen in the roosting (?) tree that I have reported previously (https://ebird.org/view/checklist/S42445216) that is roughly behind 2128 Acton (west of the street, behind the houses). Today there were three but I have seen up to six. The tree can be seen from Charlie Doerr Park from the back gate or from the sidewalk in front of the front gate (from the play structure, the tree in question is blocked by a redwood).Maybe these are the birds that are often seen during the day at Cesar Chavez & Albany Bulb & Meeker Slough? Just speculating...
As of 4:55 (1hr before sunset), none of the Kites had yet arrived at their roosting tree on Acton
